{"author":{"id":"cc8322a500b8739c77faac347808f6026d9ccb7880d0aaa7ad76754163cd7fdb"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782568926,"nonce":"pwvzgMal2cy2E0wzpOpWfQyAl7k=","kind":"spec","title":"Git-Native Knowledge Base — Architecture Design"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1782568926,"nonce":"wTLJYP2ya3nUI+VgOh9TOeQxiUg=","body":"# Git-Native Knowledge Base — Architecture Design\n\n- **Date:** 2026-06-16\n- **Status:** Draft (pending author review)\n- **Working name:** `kref` (provisional; not blocking)\n- **Type:** Architecture / multi-phase platform spec\n- **License:** GPL-3.0 (inherited from git-bug; see D6)\n\n\u003e This document is the *overarching* architecture. Only **Phase 1** is taken\n\u003e through to an implementation plan; later phases are scoped here so the\n\u003e boundaries are deliberate, not so they are built now.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Problem\n\nSpec/plan tooling (superpowers, speckit, openspec, git-adr workflows, ad-hoc\nagent notes) writes a steady stream of markdown into the working tree and\ncommits it to the code history. Three distinct costs result:\n\n1. **Working-tree clutter.** `docs/superpowers/`, `specs/`, `.plans/` get\n   globbed by agents, surface in `find`/`grep`, and bloat `git status`.\n2. **History pollution.** Spec churn, plan revisions, and brainstorm\n   transcripts interleave with code commits, degrading `git log`, `git blame`,\n   and `git bisect`.\n3. **Context-window cost.** Agents load large reference docs wholesale.\n\nTwo clarifications shaped the design:\n\n- **Durable vs. ephemeral.** The artifacts are not one class. *Durable\n  reference* (the spec a feature was built against, ADRs, project memory) has\n  long-term value. *Ephemeral exhaust* (brainstorm transcripts, superseded\n  plans) is genuine noise. They must be treated differently, not lumped.\n- **Storage vs. retrieval.** Moving bytes off the working tree fixes (1) and\n  (2). Cost (3) is a *retrieval* problem — solved by loading only what is\n  relevant, not by where data rests. The design must address both.\n\n## 2. Goals\n\n- Knowledge travels **with the repo** (clone/push/pull) without touching the\n  working tree or `main`'s commit history.\n- **Typed entries** queryable by kind/status, with a relationship graph.\n- **Both** machine access (query/RAG) **and** first-class human browsing\n  without an LLM in the loop.\n- Correct **concurrent merge** across multiple devices and multiple agents,\n  and across a team (the \"generally multi-device, often team\" case).\n- **Three visibility tiers** so personal and sensitive content never reaches a\n  shared remote.\n- A **bridge** that lets existing file-writing tools keep working while their\n  output lives in the store, not the code history.\n- **Prevention-first** handling of sensitive data, with an honest break-glass\n  prune.\n\n## 3. Non-Goals (current scope)\n\n- **Encryption at rest** (GPG / age). Desirable, explicitly deferred (§11).\n- **Vector index / semantic search.** Deferred (§11).\n- A hosted/server product. This is a local-first CLI + TUI.\n- Replacing the code's own `git` history or branching model.\n- **Forking git-bug.** We depend on its `entity/dag` package as a library; we\n  do not fork or vendor-and-diverge the application (§11 covers possible future\n  upstream collaboration).\n\n## 4. Key Decisions \u0026 Rationale\n\n| # | Decision | Rationale | Alternatives rejected |\n|---|----------|-----------|-----------------------|\n| D1 | **Build on git-bug's `entity/dag` library** (`github.com/git-bug/git-bug/entity/dag`) | It is a *publicly importable*, reusable framework for distributed, conflict-free git-object entities: Lamport-DAG merge, identity/signing, and push/pull come free, while we define our own entity types with zero baggage. Restores the original \"moves as git objects\" goal and inherits git's mature history-scrub tooling for sensitive data | **beads/Dolt:** storage is under `internal/` (importing impossible → fork-only), heavy Dolt binary, weak history-scrub, orphaned post-founder fork. **cr-sqlite:** dormant/pre-1.0 (creator departed). **File-in-repo memory tools** (DiffMem, GitAgent): re-introduce the working-tree/history clutter we exist to remove. **From-scratch CRDT:** re-treads git-bug's solved work |\n| D2 | **Unify all artifacts as typed entries** incl. docs | One store, one sync, one merge story, one tier system; a spec, ADR, memory, and issue are the same entity shape with a different `kind` | Parallel stores per artifact class (more sync/merge surface) |\n| D3 | **Three visibility tiers as separate git ref namespaces** | `dag` already stores each entity under `refs/\u003cnamespace\u003e/\u003cid\u003e`; per-tier namespaces (`kref-private` / `kref-personal` / `kref-shared`) make \"`private` never leaves\" a matter of *which refspecs are configured to push* — a structural guarantee | Tiers as a field inside one namespace (one stray push-all leaks `private`) |\n| D4 | **Bridge = configured redirect (default) + manual command + hook for hardcoded paths** | Predictable, low-magic; leans on the fact that most generators expose a configurable output path | Hook-only auto-capture (surprising); manual-only (relies on discipline) |\n| D5 | **Prevention-first sensitive-data handling**, with git-native scrub | Block ingress (scanner) is the primary control; git-object storage means the break-glass scrub uses mature `git filter-repo`/BFG rather than a weak hack | Scrub-centric design; substrates with no clean excision path |\n| D6 | **License `kref` under GPL-3.0** | Static-linking `entity/dag` (GPL-3.0) makes the binary a derivative work; matching the license keeps us upstream-compatible for the future collaboration in §11 | Permissive (MIT/Apache) — impossible while importing git-bug without relicensing it; would force a substrate change |\n\n### 4.1 Source of truth vs. derived indexes\n\nThe git-object op-DAG is the **single source of truth**. Every query surface is\na **derived, disposable index** rebuilt from entries, never authoritative:\n\n- Phase 1 uses an in-memory index (§5.1).\n- Because each entry carries structured header metadata (`kind`/`status`/`tier`/\n  `links`), projecting the same headers into SQLite or Dolt later is a pure\n  read-side addition — no migration of the source store, no lock-in.\n\nThis makes the \"no SQL\" tradeoff of D1 a deferred choice, not a one-way door.\n\n**Accepted tradeoff (D1):** `entity/dag` gives **no SQL query engine**. Typed\nfilters, the relationship/edge graph, and any `ready`-style queries become an\n**in-memory index** we build over compiled entity snapshots. At per-repo\nknowledge-base scale (thousands of entries, not millions) this is cheap, and it\nis the \"flexible/generic\" surface we wanted to own. The beads-style\ndependency/`ready`-work machinery was always tangential to a *knowledge base*.\n\n**Risk (D1):** `entity/dag` is exported but it is an application's package, not\na SemVer-stable published library. Mitigation: **pin a known-good commit** (and\nvendor if churn warrants). This risk is strictly smaller than depending on an\norphaned binary, and §11 describes the path to retire it.\n\n## 5. Architecture Overview\n\n```\n                 ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n   file-writing  │  Working tree (code)                         │\n   tools  ─────► │   .kref/workspace/   (gitignored redirect dir) │\n (superpowers,   │        │  ▲                                   │\n  speckit, …)    └────────┼──┼───────────────────────────────────┘\n                          │  │ materialize (kref show --materialize)\n                  ingest  │  │\n                          ▼  │\n        ┌───────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n        │  kref core  (Go; imports git-bug/entity/dag)             │\n        │   entity kinds = dag Definitions (spec, adr, plan,     │\n        │     memory, reference, document) over a shared op set  │\n        │   in-memory index: ReadAll → compile snapshots → query │\n        │   ingest secret-scan (gitleaks) ─► block / ►private    │\n        └───────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n            stored as git objects under refs/\u003ctier-namespace\u003e/\u003cid\u003e\n        ┌───────────┐   ┌───────────┐   ┌───────────┐\n        │ kref-private│   │kref-personal│   │ kref-shared │  ref namespaces\n        │ (no push  │   │ (personal │   │ (team     │  in the SAME repo\n        │  refspec) │   │  remote)  │   │  remote)  │\n        └───────────┘   └───────────┘   └───────────┘\n              ▲ CLI (kref …)        ▲ TUI (Bubbletea, Phase 3)\n              │ machine path      │ human path\n        sync = dag Push/Pull/Fetch ◄─ lefthook (post-merge/pre-push/post-commit)\n```\n\n### 5.1 Data model\n\nEach **kind** (`spec | adr | plan | memory | reference | document`) is a `dag`\nentity defined by a `dag.Definition` plus an operation set and a snapshot type.\nA shared operation vocabulary keeps kinds uniform:\n\n- **Operations** (each embeds `dag.OpBase`, implements `Id`/`Validate`/`Apply`):\n  `Create{kind,title}`, `SetStatus`, `SetBody`, `SetTier`, `AddLink`,\n  `RemoveLink`, `Tombstone` (soft delete).\n- **Snapshot** (compiled state): `id`, `kind`, `title`, `status`\n  (`open|active|accepted|superseded|deleted`), `tier`\n  (`private|personal|shared`), `body` (markdown), `provenance` (author identity\n  + timestamps from the op-DAG), `links` (`{to_id, type}` where type ∈\n  `relates|parent-child|supersedes|derived-from`).\n- **Index:** a process-level in-memory map built by `ReadAll` + compile,\n  supporting filter-by-kind/status/tier and link traversal. Rebuilt on demand;\n  no persisted query store in Phase 1.\n\nIdentity/attribution and signing come from git-bug's `identity` package (the\nop author is recorded in the DAG).\n\n### 5.2 Storage, tiers \u0026 sync\n\n- Entities are git objects under `refs/\u003cnamespace\u003e/\u003cid\u003e`; the **namespace is the\n  tier**: `kref-private`, `kref-personal`, `kref-shared` — all in the *same* git repo\n  as the code, never in the working tree or `main`.\n- **Sync** is `dag.Push` / `dag.Pull` / `dag.Fetch` per namespace against a\n  remote. Tier → remote refspec mapping: `private` → **no push refspec**\n  (structural guarantee); `personal` → the user's personal remote; `shared` →\n  the team remote.\n- A **tier guard** in `kref sync` refuses to push the `kref-private` namespace\n  regardless of flags.\n\n### 5.3 The capture / materialize bridge (Phase 1 core)\n\n- `.kref/workspace/` is a **gitignored** directory that *is* a materialized view\n  of the store. Generators are pointed here (superpowers' spec path is\n  configurable; speckit/openspec output paths likewise).\n- **Ingest:** `kref ingest [path]` reads new/changed markdown from the redirect\n  dir and records it as an entity (default `kind=document`), leaving the\n  working copy as a disposable projection.\n- **Materialize:** `kref show \u003cid\u003e --materialize` / `kref materialize \u003cquery\u003e`\n  compiles entity snapshots back to `.kref/workspace/...` on demand for human or\n  tool reading; the projection is never committed.\n- **Hardcoded-path fallback:** for a generator that cannot be redirected, an\n  opt-in Claude Code `Stop`/`PostToolUse` hook sweeps known paths into the\n  store and gitignores them.\n\n### 5.4 lefthook integration (Phase 2)\n\n| lefthook event | `kref` action | purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| `post-merge`, `post-checkout` | `kref sync pull` | KB matches the code state moved to |\n| `pre-push` | `kref sync push` (`shared`/`personal` only) | KB travels with the code push; tier-guard blocks `private` |\n| `post-commit` | `kref ingest` | docs produced alongside a commit are captured, never staged |\n\n## 6. Human \u0026 Machine Access\n\n- **Machine path:** the `kref` CLI (`add`, `show`, `list`, `ingest`, `link`,\n  `rm`, `sync`) with JSON output for agents.\n- **Human path:** a **Bubbletea TUI** (Phase 3) — list/filter by\n  kind+status+tier, full-text search over compiled snapshots, open an entry,\n  edit in `$EDITOR`. This is the first-class answer to \"browse without relying\n  on an LLM.\" git-bug ships a Bubbletea TUI to model on. A Markdown/JSON export\n  to a temp dir is the always-available fallback.\n\n## 7. Import Adapters (Phase 4)\n\n`kref import --from \u003cadapter\u003e \u003csource\u003e`: one adapter per source —\n`superpowers \u003cdir\u003e`, `git-adr`, `beads \u003crepo\u003e` (JSONL export), plain `notes`\n(markdown tree). Each adapter maps source records to `Create`+`SetBody`\noperations. Additive and incremental.\n\n## 8. Sensitive Data: Prevention-First, Git-Native Scrub\n\n1. **Block ingress (primary).** Ingest-time secret scan via **gitleaks**\n   (MIT, active; trufflehog as heavier alternative). A hit **blocks** ingest by\n   default and reports what/where; an explicit override routes the entry to the\n   `kref-private` namespace (never leaves the machine) rather than silently\n   allowing it.\n2. **Soft delete.** `kref rm \u003cid\u003e` appends a `Tombstone` operation: the entity\n   drops from current views and future working-set sync; the op-DAG is retained;\n   reversible. Explicitly **not** safe for secrets.\n3. **Hard purge — local (Phase 1).** `kref purge \u003cid\u003e` calls `dag.Remove`\n   (deletes the entity's `refs/\u003cnamespace\u003e/\u003cid\u003e` ref) and runs\n   `git gc --prune=now` to excise the now-unreferenced objects from the local\n   repository. **Irreversible.** By default it prompts with the full entry and\n   the caveats below; `--force` skips the prompt, `--no-gc` removes the ref only\n   (objects linger until a later gc). Note `git gc --prune=now` is repo-wide.\n4. **Distributed break-glass (Phase 2).** Once sync exists, `purge` additionally\n   force-updates affected remotes — and uses `git filter-repo`/BFG when a leaked\n   blob is entangled with other history. Git-object storage means this uses\n   *mature, battle-tested* tooling — a concrete win over the rejected SQL\n   substrates.\n5. **Assume-breach.** Purge prints: scrubbing bytes ≠ un-leaking — anything\n   already pushed must be assumed compromised; **rotate the secret** and have\n   other clones re-sync/re-clone.\n\n## 9. Phasing\n\n| Phase | Slice | Delivers |\n|---|---|---|\n| **1 (MVP)** | Go project importing `entity/dag`; entity kind(s) + shared op set + snapshot; `kref add/show/list/ingest/rm`; `kref purge` (local hard-delete + gc); redirect bridge + gitignore; `kref-private`+`kref-shared` namespaces; gitleaks ingest scan + block/►private | Doc clutter gone — durable docs live in the store as git objects, off the working tree and `main` |\n| **2** | `kref-personal` namespace + full per-tier sync routing + tier-guard + lefthook wiring; `purge` extended to force-resync remotes + `filter-repo` | Hands-off sync coupled to git; safe-enough scrub |\n| **3** | Bubbletea TUI (browse/search/edit) | Dig around without an LLM |\n| **4** | Import adapters (superpowers, git-adr, beads, notes) | Migrate existing knowledge |\n\n## 10. Open Questions / Risks\n\n- **`entity/dag` API stability.** It is an app package, not a stable library →\n  pin a commit; a Phase-1 spike confirms the custom-entity recipe against the\n  real API (the `example_test.go` `ProjectConfig` pattern).\n- **In-memory index scale.** Fine for thousands of entries; revisit if a repo's\n  KB grows into the tens of thousands.\n- **Identity \u0026 signing.** The author identity defaults to the **git user**\n  (`identity.NewFromGitUser`; `--name`/`--email` override) and is persisted via\n  `SetUserIdentity`. **Cryptographic signing is not available in git-bug\n  v0.10.1:** it signs op-pack commits only if an identity carries a signing key,\n  but exposes no public path to equip one (`storePrivate` is unexported; even\n  `git-bug user new` is keyless) and cannot delegate to your system `gpg` /\n  gpg-agent / `user.signingkey`. So attribution is by git identity (name/email),\n  **unsigned and forgeable**. See §11.\n- **Whole-namespace sync only.** `dag.Push`/`Fetch` operate on an entire\n  namespace, not per-entity — which exactly matches tier-granular sync, so this\n  is a fit, not a limitation. (Confirmed via the API map.)\n\n## 11. Deferred (captured, not scoped)\n\n- **Encryption at rest** (GPG / age) for `private`/`personal` namespaces. The\n  ideal defense for sensitive content; revisit after the core works.\n- **Vector index + semantic search** — a derived, local, `private`-tier\n  artifact rebuilt from entries; never pushed. Addresses retrieval cost (§1.3).\n- **Operation signing / non-repudiation.** git-bug's op-pack commits *can* be\n  OpenPGP-signed and verified on read, but v0.10.1 exposes no public API to give\n  an identity a signing key, and cannot use your real GPG key / gpg-agent (it\n  builds commits via go-git + in-process OpenPGP, never the `git -S` path).\n  Enabling true signing requires **forking/patching git-bug** (reverses D1's\n  no-fork stance, reintroduces a maintenance fork) or **upstreaming** the\n  key-management surface. Deferred pending that decision; until then attribution\n  is git-identity-based and unsigned.\n- **Upstream collaboration with git-bug.** Once the approach is proven, evaluate\n  extracting the shared op-DAG core into a standalone library *with* the git-bug\n  maintainers, or extending their platform if they are open to it — retiring the\n  pinned-app-package risk (§4, D1) entirely. The architecture keeps `kref`'s KB\n  semantics cleanly separated from the `dag` substrate to make this feasible."}]}